$ Simple Object Access Protocol
-
@ SOAP

SOAP is a messaging protocol specification for exchanging structured information.

The message format is based → development/XML.

The underlying protocol is most likely → development/web/HTTP (It also operates over SMTP, TCP, UDP, JMS etc). HTTP is preferred because it easily tunnels through firewalls and proxies.

{ Structure of a message

  • An *envelope* defines the message structure (header, body and fault).
  • A *set of encoding rules*
  • A convention for representing procedure calls and responses.

  The envelope and the body are required, header and fault are not.

}
{ Major characteristics

  • Extensible (security and WS-Addressing)
  • Neutral (in respect to the underlying protocol)
  • Independent (in respect to the programming language used)

}
{ Concepts

  • nodes
  • roles
  • protocol binding
  • features
  • module

}
{ Encapsulation

  • message
  • envelope
  • header block
  • header
  • body
  • fault
}
{ Example message

  { HTTP request

code {
POST /InStock HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.org
Content-Type: application/soap+xml; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 299
SOAPAction: "http://www.w3.org/2003/05/soap-envelope"

<?xml version="1.0"?>
<soap:Envelope xmlns:soap="http://www.w3.org/2003/05/soap-envelope" xmlns:m="http://www.example.org/stock/Reddy">
  <soap:Header>
  </soap:Header>
  <soap:Body>
    <m:GetStockPrice>
      <m:StockName>GOOG</m:StockName>
    </m:GetStockPrice>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>
code }

  }
  { HTTP response

code {
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: application/soap+xml; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: nnn

<?xml version="1.0"?>

<soap:Envelope
xmlns:soap="http://www.w3.org/2003/05/soap-envelope/"
soap:encodingStyle="http://www.w3.org/2003/05/soap-encoding">

<soap:Body xmlns:m="http://www.example.org/stock">
  <m:GetStockPriceResponse>
    <m:Price>34.5</m:Price>
  </m:GetStockPriceResponse>
</soap:Body>

</soap:Envelope>
code }

  }

}

